   365→## [9.0.0] (2022-01-28)
   366→
   367→### Added
   368→
   369→- simpler ECMAScript import ([#1589])
   370→- Option.preset() allows specifying value/arg for option when used without option-argument (especially optional, but also boolean option) ([#1652])
   371→- `.executableDir()` for custom search for subcommands ([#1571])
   372→- throw with helpful message if pass `Option` to `.option()` or `.requiredOption()` ([#1655])
   373→- .`error()` for generating errors from client code just like Commander generated errors, with support for  `.configureOutput()`, `.exitOverride()`, and `.showHelpAfterError()` ([#1675])
   374→- `.optsWithGlobals()` to return merged local and global options ([#1671])
   376→### Changed
   377→
   378→- *Breaking:* Commander 9 requires Node.js v12.20.0 or higher
   379→- update package-lock.json to lockfile@2 format ([#1659])
   380→- `showSuggestionAfterError` is now on by default ([#1657])
   381→- *Breaking:* default value specified for boolean option now always used as default value (see .preset() to match some previous behaviours) ([#1652])
   382→- default value for boolean option only shown in help if true/false ([#1652])
   383→- use command name as prefix for subcommand stand-alone executable name (with fallback to script name for backwards compatibility) ([#1571])
   384→- allow absolute path with `executableFile` ([#1571])
   385→- removed restriction that nested subcommands must specify `executableFile` ([#1571])
   386→- TypeScript: allow passing readonly string array to `.choices()` ([#1667])
   387→- TypeScript: allow passing readonly string array to `.parse()`, `.parseAsync()`, `.aliases()` ([#1669])
   389→### Fixed
   390→
   391→- option with optional argument not supplied on command line now works when option already has a value, whether from default value or from previous arguments ([#1652])
   393→### Removed
   394→
   395→- *Breaking:* removed internal fallback to `require.main.filename` when script not known from arguments passed to `.parse()` (can supply details using `.name()`, and `.executableDir()` or `executableFile`) ([#1571])
