   760→## [5.0.0] (2020-03-14)
   761→
   762→### Added
   763→
   764→* support for nested commands with action-handlers ([#1] [#764] [#1149])
   765→* `.addCommand()` for adding a separately configured command ([#764] [#1149])
   766→* allow a non-executable to be set as the default command ([#742] [#1149])
   767→* implicit help command when there are subcommands (previously only if executables) ([#1149])
   768→* customise implicit help command with `.addHelpCommand()` ([#1149])
   769→* display error message for unknown subcommand, by default ([#432] [#1088] [#1149])
   770→* display help for missing subcommand, by default ([#1088] [#1149])
   771→* combined short options as single argument may include boolean flags and value flag and value (e.g. `-a -b -p 80` can be written as `-abp80`) ([#1145])
   772→* `.parseOption()` includes short flag and long flag expansions ([#1145])
   773→* `.helpInformation()` returns help text as a string, previously a private routine ([#1169])
   774→* `.parse()` implicitly uses `process.argv` if arguments not specified ([#1172])
   775→* optionally specify where `.parse()` arguments "from", if not following node conventions ([#512] [#1172])
   776→* suggest help option along with unknown command error ([#1179])
   777→* TypeScript definition for `commands` property of `Command` ([#1184])
   778→* export `program` property ([#1195])
   779→* `createCommand` factory method to simplify subclassing ([#1191])
   781→### Fixed
   782→
   783→* preserve argument order in subcommands ([#508] [#962] [#1138])
   784→* do not emit `command:*` for executable subcommands ([#809] [#1149])
   785→* action handler called whether or not there are non-option arguments ([#1062] [#1149])
   786→* combining option short flag and value in single argument now works for subcommands ([#1145])
   787→* only add implicit help command when it will not conflict with other uses of argument ([#1153] [#1149])
   788→* implicit help command works with command aliases ([#948] [#1149])
   789→* options are validated whether or not there is an action handler ([#1149])
   791→### Changed
   792→
   793→* *Breaking* `.args` contains command arguments with just recognised options removed ([#1032] [#1138])
   794→* *Breaking* display error if required argument for command is missing ([#995] [#1149])
   795→* tighten TypeScript definition of custom option processing function passed to `.option()` ([#1119])
   796→* *Breaking* `.allowUnknownOption()` ([#802] [#1138])
   797→  * unknown options included in arguments passed to command action handler
   798→  * unknown options included in `.args`
   799→* only recognised option short flags and long flags are expanded (e.g. `-ab` or `--foo=bar`) ([#1145])
   800→* *Breaking* `.parseOptions()` ([#1138])
   801→  * `args` in returned result renamed `operands` and does not include anything after first unknown option
   802→  * `unknown` in returned result has arguments after first unknown option including operands, not just options and values
   803→* *Breaking* `.on('command:*', callback)` and other command events passed (changed) results from `.parseOptions`, i.e. operands and unknown  ([#1138])
   804→* refactor Option from prototype to class ([#1133])
   805→* refactor Command from prototype to class ([#1159])
   806→* changes to error handling ([#1165])
   807→  * throw for author error, not just display message
   808→  * preflight for variadic error
   809→  * add tips to missing subcommand executable
   810→* TypeScript fluent return types changed to be more subclass friendly, return `this` rather than `Command` ([#1180])
   811→* `.parseAsync` returns `Promise<this>` to be consistent with `.parse()` ([#1180])
   812→* update dependencies
   814→### Removed
   815→
   816→* removed EventEmitter from TypeScript definition for Command, eliminating implicit peer dependency on `@types/node` ([#1146])
   817→* removed private function `normalize` (the functionality has been integrated into `parseOptions`) ([#1145])
   818→* `parseExpectedArgs` is now private ([#1149])
   820→### Migration Tips
   821→
   822→If you use `.on('command:*')` or more complicated tests to detect an unrecognised subcommand, you may be able to delete the code and rely on the default behaviour.
