Readme.md
     1→# Commander.js
     2→
     3→[![Build Status](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/workflows/build/badge.svg)](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/actions?query=workflow%3A%22build%22)
     4→[![NPM Version](http://img.shields.io/npm/v/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://www.npmjs.org/package/commander)
     5→[![NPM Downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dm/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://npmcharts.com/compare/commander?minimal=true)
     6→[![Install Size](https://packagephobia.now.sh/badge?p=commander)](https://packagephobia.now.sh/result?p=commander)
    61→## Installation
    62→
    63→```sh
    64→npm install commander
    65→```
    67→## Quick Start
    68→
    69→You write code to describe your command line interface.
    70→Commander looks after parsing the arguments into options and command-arguments,
    71→displays usage errors for problems, and implements a help system.
   147→## Declaring _program_ variable
   148→
   149→Commander exports a global object which is convenient for quick programs.
   150→This is used in the examples in this README for brevity.
   177→## Options
   178→
   179→Options are defined with the `.option()` method, also serving as documentation for the options. Each option can have a short flag (single character) and a long name, separated by a comma, a space, or a vertical bar (`|`). To allow a wider range of short-ish flags than just single characters, you may also have two long options.
   211→### Common option types, boolean and value
   212→
   213→The two most used option types are a boolean option, and an option which takes its value
   214→from the following argument (declared with angle brackets like `--expect <value>`). Both are `undefined` unless specified on command line.
   254→### Default option value
   255→
   256→You can specify a default value for an option.
   276→### Other option types, negatable boolean and boolean|value
   277→
   278→You can define a boolean option long name with a leading `no-` to set the option value to `false` when used.
   279→Defined alone, this also makes the option `true` by default.
   342→### Required option
   343→
   344→You may specify a required (mandatory) option using `.requiredOption()`. The option must have a value after parsing, usually specified on the command line, or perhaps from a default value (e.g., from environment). 
   362→### Variadic option
   363→
   364→You may make an option variadic by appending `...` to the value placeholder when declaring the option. On the command line you
   365→can then specify multiple option-arguments, and the parsed option value will be an array. The extra arguments
   366→are read until the first argument starting with a dash. The special argument `--` stops option processing entirely. If a value
   367→is specified in the same argument as the option, then no further values are read.
   396→### Version option
   397→
   398→The optional `.version()` method adds handling for displaying the command version. The default option flags are `-V` and `--version`. When used, the command prints the version number and exits.
   416→### More configuration
   417→
   418→You can add most options using the `.option()` method, but there are some additional features available
   419→by constructing an `Option` explicitly for less common cases.
   459→### Custom option processing
   460→
   461→You may specify a function to do custom processing of option-arguments. The callback function receives two parameters,
   462→the user specified option-argument and the previous value for the option. It returns the new value for the option.
   523→## Commands
   524→
   525→You can specify (sub)commands using `.command()` or `.addCommand()`. There are two ways these can be implemented: using an `.action()` handler attached to the command; or as a stand-alone executable file. (More detail about this later.)
   567→### Command-arguments
   568→
   569→For subcommands, you can specify the argument syntax in the call to `.command()` (as shown above). This
   570→is the only method usable for subcommands implemented using a stand-alone executable.
   613→#### More configuration
   614→
   615→There are some additional features available by constructing an `Argument` explicitly for less common cases.
   625→#### Custom argument processing
   626→
   627→You may specify a function to do custom processing of command-arguments (like for option-arguments).
   628→The callback function receives two parameters, the user specified command-argument and the previous value for the argument.
   629→It returns the new value for the argument.
   648→### Action handler
   649→
   650→The action handler gets passed a parameter for each command-argument you declared, and two additional parameters
   651→which are the parsed options and the command object itself.
   700→### Stand-alone executable (sub)commands
   701→
   702→When `.command()` is invoked with a description argument, this tells Commander that you're going to use stand-alone executables for subcommands.
   703→Commander will search the files in the directory of the entry script for a file with the name combination `command-subcommand` (like `pm-install` or `pm-search` in the example below). The search includes trying common file extensions, like `.js`.
   704→You may specify a custom name (and path) with the `executableFile` configuration option.
   705→You may specify a custom search directory for subcommands with `.executableDir()`.
   725→### Life cycle hooks
   726→
   727→You can add callback hooks to a command for life cycle events.
   754→## Automated help
   755→
   756→The help information is auto-generated based on the information commander already knows about your program. The default
   757→help option is `-h,--help`.
   787→### Custom help
   788→
   789→You can add extra text to be displayed along with the built-in help.
   830→### Display help after errors
   831→
   832→The default behaviour for usage errors is to just display a short error message.
   833→You can change the behaviour to show the full help or a custom help message after an error.
   860→### Display help from code
   861→
   862→`.help()`: display help information and exit immediately. You can optionally pass `{ error: true }` to display on stderr and exit with an error status.
   868→### .name
   869→
   870→The command name appears in the help, and is also used for locating stand-alone executable subcommands.
   884→### .usage
   885→
   886→This allows you to customise the usage description in the first line of the help. Given:
   900→### .description and .summary
   901→
   902→The description appears in the help for the command. You can optionally supply a shorter
   903→summary to use when listed as a subcommand of the program.
   914→### .helpOption(flags, description)
   915→
   916→By default, every command has a help option. You may change the default help flags and description. Pass `false` to disable the built-in help option.
   925→### .helpCommand()
   926→
   927→A help command is added by default if your command has subcommands. You can explicitly turn the implicit help command on or off with `.helpCommand(true)` and `.helpCommand(false)`.
   937→### Help Groups
   938→
   939→The help by default lists options under the the heading `Options:` and commands under `Commands:`. You can create your own groups
   940→with different headings. 
   947→### More configuration
   948→
   949→The built-in help is formatted using the `Help` class.
   950→You can configure the help by modifying data properties and methods using `.configureHelp()`, or by subclassing `Help` using `.createHelp()` .
   956→## Custom event listeners
   957→
   958→You can execute custom actions by listening to `command` and `option` events.
   966→## Bits and pieces
   967→
   968→### .parse() and .parseAsync()
   969→
   970→Call with no parameters to parse `process.argv`. Detects Electron and special node options like `node --eval`. Easy mode!
   988→### Parsing Configuration
   989→
   990→If the default parsing does not suit your needs, there are some behaviours to support other usage patterns.
  1023→### Legacy options as properties
  1024→
  1025→Before Commander 7, the option values were stored as properties on the command.
  1026→This was convenient to code, but the downside was possible clashes with
  1027→existing properties of `Command`. 
  1042→### TypeScript
  1043→
  1044→**extra-typings:** There is an optional project to infer extra type information from the option and argument definitions.
  1045→This adds strong typing to the options returned by `.opts()` and the parameters to `.action()`.
  1046→For more, see the repo: [commander-js/extra-typings](https://github.com/commander-js/extra-typings).
  1058→### createCommand()
  1059→
  1060→This factory function creates a new command. It is exported and may be used instead of using `new`, like:
  1071→### Node options such as `--harmony`
  1072→
  1073→You can enable `--harmony` option in two ways:
  1078→### Debugging stand-alone executable subcommands
  1079→
  1080→An executable subcommand is launched as a separate child process.
  1087→### npm run-script
  1088→
  1089→By default, when you call your program using `run-script`, `npm` will parse any options on the command-line and they will not reach your program. Use
  1090→ `--` to stop the npm option parsing and pass through all the arguments.
  1098→### Display error
  1099→
  1100→This routine is available to invoke the Commander error handling for your own error conditions. (See also the next section about exit handling.)
  1110→### Override exit and output handling
  1111→
  1112→By default, Commander calls `process.exit()` when it detects errors, or after displaying the help or version. You can override
  1113→this behaviour and optionally supply a callback. The default override throws a `CommanderError`.
  1154→### Additional documentation
  1155→
  1156→There is more information available about:
  1164→## Support
  1165→
  1166→The current version of Commander is fully supported on Long Term Support versions of Node.js, and requires at least v20.
  1172→### Commander for enterprise
  1173→
  1174→Available as part of the Tidelift Subscription
Readme_zh-CN.md
     1→# Commander.js
     2→
     3→[![Build Status](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/workflows/build/badge.svg)](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/actions?query=workflow%3A%22build%22)
     4→[![NPM Version](http://img.shields.io/npm/v/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://www.npmjs.org/package/commander)
     5→[![NPM Downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dm/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://npmcharts.com/compare/commander?minimal=true)
     6→[![Install Size](https://packagephobia.now.sh/badge?p=commander)](https://packagephobia.now.sh/result?p=commander)
    59→## 安装
    60→
    61→```sh
    62→npm install commander
    63→```
    65→## 快速开始
    66→
    67→编写代码来描述你的命令行界面。
    68→Commander 负责将参数解析为选项和命令参数，为问题显示使用错误，并实现一个有帮助的系统。
   144→## 声明 program 变量
   145→
   146→为简化使用，Commander 提供了一个全局对象。本文档的示例代码均按此方法使用：
   173→## 选项
   174→
   175→Commander 使用`.option()`方法来定义选项，同时可以附加选项的简介。每个选项可以定义一个短选项名称（-后面接单个字符）和一个长选项名称（--后面接一个或多个单词），使用逗号、空格或`|`分隔。
   200→### 常用选项类型，boolean 型选项和带参数选项
   201→
   202→有两种最常用的选项，一类是 boolean 型选项，选项无需配置参数，另一类选项则可以设置参数（使用尖括号声明在该选项后，如`--expect <value>`）。如果在命令行中不指定具体的选项及参数，则会被定义为`undefined`。
   242→### 选项的默认值
   243→
   244→选项可以设置一个默认值。
   264→### 其他的选项类型，取反选项，以及可选参数的选项
   265→
   266→可以定义一个以`no-`开头的 boolean 型长选项。在命令行中使用该选项时，会将对应选项的值置为`false`。当只定义了带`no-`的选项，未定义对应不带`no-`的选项时，该选项的默认值会被置为`true`。
   325→### 必填选项
   326→
   327→通过`.requiredOption()`方法可以设置选项为必填。必填选项要么设有默认值，要么必须在命令行中输入，对应的属性字段在解析时必定会有赋值。该方法其余参数与`.option()`一致。
   343→### 变长参数选项
   344→
   345→定义选项时，可以通过使用`...`来设置参数为可变长参数。在命令行中，用户可以输入多个参数，解析后会以数组形式存储在对应属性字段中。在输入下一个选项前（`-`或`--`开头），用户输入的指令均会被视作变长参数。与普通参数一样的是，可以通过`--`标记当前命令的结束。
   374→### 版本选项
   375→
   376→`.version()`方法可以设置版本，其默认选项为`-V`和`--version`，设置了版本后，命令行会输出当前的版本号。
   393→### 其他选项配置
   394→
   395→大多数情况下，选项均可通过`.option()`方法添加。但对某些不常见的用例，也可以直接构造`Option`对象，对选项进行更详尽的配置。
   433→### 自定义选项处理
   434→
   435→选项的参数可以通过自定义函数来处理，该函数接收两个参数，即用户新输入的参数值和当前已有的参数值（即上一次调用自定义处理函数后的返回值），返回新的选项参数值。
   496→## 命令
   497→
   498→通过`.command()`或`.addCommand()`可以配置命令，有两种实现方式：为命令绑定处理函数，或者将命令单独写成一个可执行文件（详述见后文）。子命令支持嵌套（[示例代码](./examples/nestedCommands.js)）。
   530→### 命令参数
   531→
   532→如上所述，子命令的参数可以通过`.command()`指定。对于有独立可执行文件的子命令来说，参数只能以这种方法指定。而对其他子命令，参数也可用以下方法。
   570→#### 其他参数配置
   571→
   572→有少数附加功能可以直接构造`Argument`对象，对参数进行更详尽的配置。
   582→#### 自定义参数处理
   583→
   584→选项的参数可以通过自定义函数来处理（与处理选项参数时类似），该函数接收两个参数：用户新输入的参数值和当前已有的参数值（即上一次调用自定义处理函数后的返回值），返回新的命令参数值。
   603→### 处理函数
   604→
   605→命令处理函数的参数，为该命令声明的所有参数，除此之外还会附加两个额外参数：一个是解析出的选项，另一个则是该命令对象自身。
   653→### 独立的可执行（子）命令
   654→
   655→当`.command()`带有描述参数时，就意味着使用独立的可执行文件作为子命令。
   656→Commander 会尝试在入口脚本的目录中搜索名称组合为 `command-subcommand` 的文件，如以下示例中的 `pm-install` 或 `pm-search`。搜索包括尝试常见的文件扩展名，如`.js`。
   657→你可以使用 `executableFile` 配置选项指定自定义名称（和路径）。
   658→你可以使用 `.executableDir()` 为子命令指定自定义搜索目录。
   678→### 生命周期钩子
   679→
   680→可以在命令的生命周期事件上设置回调函数。
   705→## 自动化帮助信息
   706→
   707→帮助信息是 Commander 基于你的程序自动生成的，默认的帮助选项是`-h,--help`。
   734→### 自定义帮助
   735→
   736→可以添加额外的帮助信息，与内建的帮助一同展示。
   777→### 在出错后展示帮助信息
   778→
   779→默认情况下，出现命令用法错误时只会显示错误信息。可以选择在出错后展示完整的帮助或自定义的帮助信息。
   805→### 使用代码展示帮助信息
   806→
   807→`.help()`：展示帮助信息并退出。可以通过传入`{ error: true }`来让帮助信息从 stderr 输出，并以代表错误的状态码退出程序。
   813→### .name
   814→
   815→命令名称出现在帮助中，也用于定位独立的可执行子命令。
   826→### .usage
   827→
   828→通过这个选项可以修改帮助信息的首行提示，例如：
   842→### .description 和 .summary
   843→
   844→description 出现在命令的帮助中。当列为程序的子命令时，你可以选择提供更短的 summary 以供使用。
   855→### .helpOption(flags, description)
   856→
   857→每一个命令都带有一个默认的帮助选项。你可以改变 `flags` 和 `description` 参数。传入 `false` 则会禁用内建的帮助信息。
   864→### .addHelpCommand()
   865→
   866→如果一个命令拥有子命令，它也将有一个默认的帮助子命令。使用`.addHelpCommand()`和`.addHelpCommand(false)`可以打开或关闭默认的帮助子命令。
   874→### 其他帮助配置
   875→
   876→内建帮助信息通过`Help`类进行格式化。如有需要，可以使用`.configureHelp()`来更改其数据属性和方法，或使用`.createHelp()`来创建子类，从而配置`Help`类的行为。
   895→## 自定义事件监听
   896→
   897→监听命令和选项可以执行自定义函数。
   905→## 零碎知识
   906→
   907→### .parse() 和 .parseAsync()
   908→
   909→`.parse`的第一个参数是要解析的字符串数组，也可以省略参数而使用`process.argv`。
   925→### 解析配置
   926→
   927→当默认的解析方式无法满足需要，Commander 也提供了其他的解析行为。
   956→### 作为属性的遗留选项
   957→
   958→在 Commander 7 以前，选项的值是作为属性存储在命令对象上的。
   959→这种处理方式便于实现，但缺点在于，选项可能会与`Command`的已有属性相冲突。通过使用`.storeOptionsAsProperties()`，可以恢复到这种旧的处理方式，并可以不加改动地继续运行遗留代码。
   972→### TypeScript
   973→
   974→如果你使用 ts-node，并有`.ts`文件作为独立可执行文件，那么需要用 node 运行你的程序以使子命令能正确调用，例如：
   980→### createCommand()
   981→
   982→使用这个工厂方法可以创建新命令，此时不需要使用`new`，如
   991→### Node 选项，如 --harmony
   992→
   993→要使用`--harmony`等选项有以下两种方式：
   998→### 调试子命令
   999→
  1000→一个可执行的子命令会作为单独的子进程执行。
  1006→### 显示错误
  1007→
  1008→你可用于针对自己的错误情况调用 Commander 错误处理。（另请参阅下一节有关退出处理的内容）
  1017→### 重写退出和输出
  1018→
  1019→默认情况下，在检测到错误、打印帮助信息或版本信息时 Commander 会调用`process.exit`方法。其默认实现会抛出一个`CommanderError`，可以重写该方法并提供一个回调函数（可选）。
  1054→### 其他文档
  1055→
  1056→请参考关于如下话题的其他文档：
  1061→## 支持
  1062→
  1063→当前版本的 Commander 在 LTS 版本的 Node.js 上完全支持。并且至少需要 v18。
  1064→（使用更低版本 Node.js 的用户建议安装更低版本的 Commander）
  1068→### 企业使用 Commander
  1069→
  1070→作为 Tidelift 订阅的一部分。
SECURITY.md
     1→# Security Policy
     2→
     3→To report a security vulnerability, please use the
     4→[Tidelift security contact](https://tidelift.com/security).
     5→Tidelift will coordinate the fix and disclosure.
docs/deprecated.md
     1→# Deprecated
     2→
     3→These features are deprecated, which means they may go away in a future major version of Commander.
     4→They are currently still available for backwards compatibility, but should not be used in new code.
    22→### RegExp .option() parameter
    23→
    24→The `.option()` method allowed a RegExp as the third parameter to restrict what values were accepted.
    34→### noHelp
    35→
    36→This was an option passed to `.command()` to hide the command from the built-in help:
    44→### Callback to .help() and .outputHelp()
    45→
    46→These routines allowed a callback parameter to process the built-in help before display.
    62→### .on('--help')
    63→
    64→This was the way to add custom help after the built-in help. From Commander v3.0.0 this used the custom long help option flags, if changed.
    87→### .on('command:*')
    88→
    89→This was emitted when the command argument did not match a known subcommand (as part of the implementation of `.command('*')`).
    98→### .command('*')
    99→
   100→This was used to add a default command to the program.
   118→### cmd.description(cmdDescription, argDescriptions)
   119→
   120→This was used to add command argument descriptions for the help.
   141→### InvalidOptionArgumentError
   142→
   143→This was used for throwing an error from custom option processing, for a nice error message.
   171→### Import from `commander/esm.mjs`
   172→
   173→The first support for named imports required an explicit entry file.
   187→### cmd._args
   188→
   189→This was always private, but was previously the only way to access the command `Argument` array.
   203→### .addHelpCommand(string|boolean|undefined)
   204→
   205→This was originally used with a variety of parameters, but not by passing a Command object despite the "add" name.
   227→## Removed
   228→
   229→### Short option flag longer than a single character
   230→
   231→Short option flags like `-ws` were never supported, but the old README did not make this clear. The README now states that short options are a single character.
   238→### Default import of global Command object
   239→
   240→The default import was a global Command object.
docs/help-in-depth.md
     1→# Help in Depth
     2→
     3→The built-in help is formatted using the Help class.
     4→You can configure the Help behaviour by modifying data properties and methods using `.configureHelp()`, or by subclassing using `.createHelp()` if you prefer.
    20→## Data Properties
    21→
    22→The data properties are:
    34→## Stringify and Style
    35→
    36→The `Help` object has narrowly focused methods to allow customising the displayed help.
   118→## Layout
   119→
   120→Utility methods which control the layout include `padWidth`, `boxWrap`, and `formatItem`. These can be overridden to change the layout or replace with an alternative implementation.
docs/options-in-depth.md
     2→# Options in Depth
     3→
     4→The README covers declaring and using options, and mostly parsing will work the way you and your users expect. This page covers some special cases
     5→and subtle issues in depth.
    15→## Options taking varying numbers of option-arguments
    16→
    17→Certain options take a varying number of arguments:
    30→### Parsing ambiguity
    31→
    32→There is a potential downside to be aware of. If a command has both
    33→command-arguments and options with varying option-arguments, this introduces a parsing ambiguity which may affect the user of your program.
    34→Commander looks for option-arguments first, but the user may
    35→intend the argument following the option as a command or command-argument.
    79→#### Alternative: Make `--` part of your syntax
    80→
    81→Rather than trying to teach your users what `--` does, you could just make it part of your syntax.
   104→#### Alternative: Put options last
   105→
   106→Commander follows the GNU convention for parsing and allows options before or after the command-arguments, or intermingled.
   107→So by putting the options last, the command-arguments do not get confused with the option-arguments.
   126→#### Alternative: Use options instead of command-arguments
   127→
   128→This is a bit more radical, but completely avoids the parsing ambiguity!
   148→## Combining short options, and options taking arguments
   149→
   150→Multiple boolean short options can be combined after a single `-`, like `ls -al`. You can also include just
   151→a single short option which might take a value, as any following characters will
   152→be taken as the value.
   191→### Combining short options as if boolean
   192→
   193→Before Commander v5, combining a short option and the value was not supported, and combined short flags were always expanded.
   194→So `-avl` expanded to `-a -v -l`.
docs/parsing-and-hooks.md
     1→# Parsing life cycle and hooks
     2→
     3→The processing starts with an array of args. Each command processes and removes the options it understands, and passes the remaining args to the next subcommand.
     4→The final command calls the action handler.
docs/release-policy.md
     1→# Release Policy
     2→
     3→We follow [Semantic Versioning](http://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html), and limit breaking changes to major versions.
docs/terminology.md
     1→# Terminology
     2→
     3→The command line arguments are made up of options, option-arguments, commands, and command-arguments.
docs/zh-CN/不再推荐使用的功能.md
     1→# 不再推荐使用的功能
     2→
     3→本文中列出的功能不再推荐使用。它们在 Commander 未来的主要版本（major version）中可能被移除。为保证后向兼容，这些功能目前还可以使用，但它们不应被用在新代码中。
    18→## .option() 方法的正则表达式参数
    19→
    20→`.option()`方法可以接受一个正则表达式作为第三个参数，以规定可以接受的选项参数值。
    30→## noHelp
    31→
    32→此选项曾被用作传入`.command()`方法，以在内建的帮助信息中隐藏该命令：
    40→## 默认导入的全局 Command 对象
    41→
    42→Commander 的默认导入曾是一个全局的`Command`对象。
    61→## .help() 与 .outputHelp() 的回调函数参数
    62→
    63→这两个方法曾允许传入一个回调函数，以在展示前处理帮助信息。
    79→## .on('--help')
    80→
    81→此功能曾被用作在内建的帮助信息后输出自定义的帮助信息。自 Commander v3.0.0 起，如果有自定义的帮助选项，则此方法使用该自定义的帮助选项。
   104→## .on('command:*')
   105→
   106→当命令参数与已知子命令不匹配时发出此消息（作为 `.command('')` 实现的一部分）。
   114→## .command('*')
   115→
   116→这用于向程序添加默认命令。
   134→## cmd.description(cmdDescription, argDescriptions)
   135→
   136→此功能曾用来为命令参数添加描述信息。
   157→## InvalidOptionArgumentError
   158→
   159→此类曾被用来在自定义选项处理中抛出错误，以显示错误信息。
   187→## 短选项标志长于单个字符
   188→
   189→短选项从未支持像 `-ws` 的标识，但旧的 README 并没有明确说明这一点。README 现在声明短选项是单个字符。
docs/zh-CN/可变参数的选项.md
     1→# 可变参数的选项
     2→
     3→README 文档介绍了选项的声明与使用。大多数情况下，选项的解析行为，与您和您程序用户的期望相符。本文将详述一些特殊用例和细节问题。
    26→## 解析中的歧义
    27→
    28→解析选项时，有一些潜在的问题值得注意。当一个命令既有命令参数，又有选项的时候，在解析过程中有可能出现歧义。这可能会影响用户使用您的程序。
    29→Commander 首先解析选项的参数，而用户有可能想将选项后面跟的参数作为命令，或是作为命令参数进行解析。
    73→### 方案一：让`--`成为语法的一部分
    74→
    75→与其让用户理解`--`的用法，您也可以直接把它作为程序语法的一部分。
    98→### 方案二：把选项放在最后
    99→
   100→Commander 遵循 GNU 解析命令的惯例，允许选项出现在命令参数之前或者之后，也可以将选项和命令参数相互穿插。
   101→因此，通过要求把选项放在最后，命令参数就不会和选项参数相混淆。
   120→### 方案三：使用选项替代命令参数
   121→
   122→这个方案虽然有点激进，但是可以完美避免解析中的歧义。
   142→## 合并短选项和带有参数的选项
   143→
   144→多个 boolean 型的短选项可以合并起来写在同一个`-`号后面，比如`ls -al`。同时，你也可以在其中包括一个接受参数的短选项，此时，任何跟在其后的字符都将被视作这个选项的值。
   183→### 将短选项视作 boolean 类型选项合并
   184→
   185→在 Commander v5 之前，并不支持合并短选项和值。合并的 boolean 类型选项会被展开。
   186→因此，`-avl`将被展开为`-a -v -l`。
docs/zh-CN/术语表.md
     1→# 术语表
     2→
     3→命令行参数由选项（options）、选项参数（option-arguments）、命令（commands），以及命令参数（command-arguments）组成。
